program, please [applause].

00:05:23.080 --> 00:05:28.500
My poem is called In This
Place, an American Lyric.

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:36.430
There's a poem in this place
in the footfalls in the halls

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:39.850
in the quiet beat of the seats.

00:05:39.850 --> 00:05:43.200
It is here, at the curtain of day,

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:48.390
where America writes a lyric
you must whisper to say.

00:05:48.390 --> 00:05:53.700
There's a poem in this place in
the heavy grace, the lined face

00:05:53.700 --> 00:06:00.010 position:56%
of this noble building,
collections burned and reborn twice.

00:06:00.010 --> 00:06:05.900
There's a poem in Boston's Copley
Square where protest chants tear

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:08.200 position:56%
through the air like sheets of rain,

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:13.480
where love of the many
swallows hatred of the few.

00:06:13.480 --> 00:06:19.590
There's a poem in Charlottesville
where tiki torches string a ring

00:06:19.590 --> 00:06:24.150
of flame tight round the
wrist of night where men

00:06:24.150 --> 00:06:30.930
so white they gleam blue seem
like statues where men heap

00:06:30.930 --> 00:06:37.150
that long wax burning ever higher
where Heather Heyer blooms forever

00:06:37.150 --> 00:06:39.540
in a meadow of resistance.

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:44.540
There's a poem in the great
sleeping giant of Lake Michigan,

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:49.090
defiantly raising its big
blue head to Milwaukee

00:06:49.090 --> 00:06:56.680
and Chicago a poem begun long
ago, blazed into frozen soil,

00:06:56.680 --> 00:06:59.850
strutting upward and aglow.

00:06:59.850 --> 00:07:05.930
There's a poem in Florida, in
East Texas, where streets swell

00:07:05.930 --> 00:07:11.980
into a nexus of rivers, cows afloat
like mottled buoys in the brown,

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:14.630
where courage is now so common

00:07:14.630 --> 00:07:21.180
that 23-year-old Jesus Contreras
rescues people from floodwaters.

00:07:21.180 --> 00:07:26.460
There's a poem in Los Angeles
yawning wide as the Pacific tide

00:07:26.460 --> 00:07:32.280 position:56%
where a single mother swelters in a
windowless classroom, teaching black

00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:35.830
and brown students in Watts
to spell out their thoughts

00:07:35.830 --> 00:07:41.210
so her daughter might
write this poem for you.

00:07:41.210 --> 00:07:46.280
There's a lyric in California
where thousands of students march

00:07:46.280 --> 00:07:50.490
for blocks, undocumented
and unafraid;

00:07:50.490 --> 00:07:55.360
where my friend Rosa finds the
power to blossom in deadlock,

00:07:55.360 --> 00:07:58.740
her spirit the bedrock
of her community.

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:05.170
She knows hope is like a stubborn
ship gripping a dock, a truth:

00:08:05.170 --> 00:08:09.770
that you can't stop a
dreamer or knock down a dream.

00:08:09.770 --> 00:08:16.450
How could this not be her city su
nacion our country our America,

00:08:16.450 --> 00:08:22.550
our American lyric to write a
poem by the people, the poor,

00:08:22.550 --> 00:08:27.450
the Protestant, the Muslim, the
Jew, the native, the immigrant,

00:08:27.450 --> 00:08:33.160
the black, the brown, the blind,
the brave, the undocumented

00:08:33.160 --> 00:08:37.740 position:56%
and undeterred, the woman, the man,
the nonbinary, the white, the trans,

00:08:37.740 --> 00:08:43.870
the ally to all of
the above and more?

00:08:43.870 --> 00:08:45.510
Tyrants fear the poet.

00:08:45.510 --> 00:08:50.850
Now that we know it
we can't blow it.

00:08:50.850 --> 00:08:54.950
We owe it to show it not slow
it although it hurts to sew it

00:08:54.950 --> 00:08:57.180
when the world skirts below it.

00:08:57.180 --> 00:09:02.930
Hope, we must bestow it like a wick
in the poet so it can grow, lit,

00:09:02.930 --> 00:09:10.090
bringing with it stories to rewrite
the story of a Texas city depleted

00:09:10.090 --> 00:09:12.890
